</p></div>
<p>It comes at a rocky time for Rare. Acquired by Microsoft back in 2002, the studio has struggled to reach the same success it had on the N64. Live-service pirate game <a href="https://www.eurogamer.net/games/sea-of-thieves">Sea of Thieves</a>, released in 2019, is its biggest recent hit, incidentally directed by Mayles.</p>
<p>Yet in July <a href="https://www.eurogamer.net/microsoft-begins-substantial-layoff-process-across-gaming-division-king-and-zenimax-impacted">Microsoft laid off a number of employees across its gaming division</a>. Rare's long-in-development Everwild was cancelled, as was The Initiative's Perfect Dark - a reboot of Rare's shooter series.</p>
<p>Executive producer Louise O'Connor also reportedly left the company alongside Mayles, having joined the studio in 1999 for N64 platformer Conker's Bad Fur Day.</p>
<p>As such, it's now unclear what Rare is working on next beyond continued development on Sea of Thieves. The departure of top developers further puts the studio's future into question.</p>
<p><a href="https://www.eurogamer.net/first-screenshots-of-rares-ill-fated-everwild-emerge-thanks-to-artists-portfolio-website">First screenshots of Everwild leaked</a> earlier this week, providing a look at the game's UI. Little was known about the game beyond the trailers officially released. Similarly, details on the<a href="https://www.eurogamer.net/perfect-dark-reboot-leak-fresh-info-suggests-studio-saw-gap-in-the-market-with-metal-gear-solid-and-bond-absent"> Perfect Dark reboot leaked last month</a>.</p>



